heckboxes, and codeCheckbox. Each of these has attributes, HTML output examples, and JSP usage examples to show how they render in practice. I'm realizing the RST heading hierarchy depends on the order they appear in the document, so the dashes and tildes establish the levels as I encounter them. Looking at this section, the h2 \"コード値の表示方法\" contains multiple h3 subsections for each tag type, and since the content is substantial with descriptions and attribute tables, I should split these h3 sections separately rather than keeping them all under one h2. JSP examples show the key attributes like `name`, `codeId`, `pattern`, and `labelPattern` with their placeholder values ($VALUE$, $NAME$, $SHORTNAME$, $OPTIONALNAME$). For the radio button and checkbox tags, the HTML output demonstrates the id format patterns they generate. The checkbox tag has its own attribute set including `offCodeValue`. These are all Layer B specifications that define the implementation contract. Generating the custom tag reference table... Now I'm detailing the codeSelect tag which generates a select element with options from the code tables, including the ability to add a \"no selection\" option at the top with customizable labeling. For codeRadioButtons, I'm describing how it creates multiple radio input elements where each id follows a specific naming convention. Now I'm looking at the attributes for the codeCheckbox tag itself—value is required and defaults to \"1\" when checked, while codeId is mandatory. The optionColumnName specifies which column to retrieve, labelPattern formats the label with a default of \"$NAME$\", and offCodeValue handles the unchecked state, automatically using the remaining code value from the codeId if not explicitly set.\n\nFor the JSON structure, I'm organizing the sections by their IDs: s1 covers the overview table of input custom tags including text, textarea, password, hidden, radio buttons, checkboxes, and select variants, while s2 focuses on the code value